man speaking.

âThis is the gentleman, Silas,â said the woman, speaking over
Lestrangeâs shoulder. Then she withdrew and closed the door.

âTake a chair, sir,â said the sea captain, flapping one of his hands on
the counterpane as if in wearied protest against his own helplessness.
âI havenât the pleasure of your name, but the missus tells me youâre
come about the advertisement I lit on yester-even.â

He took a paper, folded small, that lay beside him, and held it out to
his visitor. It was a _Sidney Bulletin_ three years old.

âYes,â said Lestrange, looking at the paper; âthat is my advertisement.â

âWell, itâs strangeâvery strange,â said Captain Fountain, âthat I
should have lit on it only yesterday. Iâve had it all three years in my
chest, the way old papers get lying at the bottom with odds and ends.
Mightnât aâ seen it now, only the missus cleared the raffle out of the
